rch on Brooklyn Heights in 1931. She served as president of the Grace Church Girls Friendly Society for fifty years and spent her summers at Northeast Harbor, Maine, as patron of the Seal Cove Mission."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Last of her generation","body":"She never married and spent her final decades at the family mansion with her sister Julia, until Julia died in 1937 — three years before her. At her death, journalists described her as the last surviving member of her generation in one of New York's most prominent families."}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Anna Jay Pierrepont","first_name":"Anna","middle_name":"Jay","maiden_name":"Pierrepont","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://images.findagrave.com/photos/2018/77/58486813_de529317-8e82-4fec-a795-8943d37c2587.png"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"anna-pierrepont-1861"},"H00976":{"id":"H00976","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00388","mother_id":"X00494"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Moffat, R. Burnham. Pierrepont Genealogies from Norman times to 1913 (1913)"},{"short":"Brooklyn Historical Society: Pierrepont Family Papers ARC.263"}],"birth":{"year":1768},"death":{"year":1838},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00495","children_ids":["HD1533","HD1534","HD1589","HD1590","HD1591","HD1592","HD1593","HD1594","HD1595","HD1596","HD1597","HD1598","X00518","X00975"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1802,"date_month":1,"date_day":21}],"cross_connections":[],"gender":"male","former_ids":["H00976"],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hezekiah_Pierrepont"},"number_of_marriages":1,"bio":{"display_name":"Hezekiah Beers Pierrepont Pierpont","first_name":"Hezekiah","last_name":"Pierpont","middle_name":"Beers Pierrepont","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/30/Hezekiah_Beers_Pierrepont.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Aged Brooklyn gin a full year for mellowness","body":"In 1801 he bought Philip Livingston's old brewery on the Brooklyn waterfront and converted it to the Anchor Gin Distillery. The site closed in 1819 and is now part of One Brooklyn Bridge Park."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Half a million acres at eight cents apiece","body":"His 1802 marriage to Anna Maria Constable made him heir to her father William Constable's Northern New York holdings. The land had been bought decades earlier when there was no buyer for it."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"Proposed the Brooklyn Heights Promenade","body":"He sketched a public walkway along the bluffs above the harbor more than a century before it was built. The Promenade as it exists today follows the route he proposed."},{"number":4,"category":"career","header":"Pirates seized his ship and bankrupted him","body":"The Confederacy was taken at sea in 1797 carrying his firm's cargo. The loss ended his Paris-based mercantile career and forced him home to start again."},{"number":5,"category":"character","header":"Witnessed Robespierre's execution from the crowd","body":"He spent seven years in France during the 1790s tending his firm's shipments. He was in Paris for the Reign of Terror and saw the head of the Jacobin regime guillotined."}],"slug":"hezekiah-pierpont-1768"},"X00495":{"id":"X00495","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1783},"death":{"year":1859},"gender":"female","marriages":[{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"H00976","date_year":1802,"date_month":1,"date_day":21,"children_ids":["HD1533","HD1534","HD1589","HD1590","HD1591","HD1592","HD1593","HD1594","HD1595","HD1596","HD1597","HD1598","X00518","X00975"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Anna Maria Constable","first_name":"Anna","middle_name":"Maria","maiden_name":"Constable","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://americanaristocracy.com/storage/11475/Screen-Shot-2021-07-26-at-12.20.20.png"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"anna-constable-1783"},"H00388":{"id":"H00388","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1740,"month":5,"day":21,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1805,"month":10,"day":8,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM009","plot_notes":"Grove Street Cemetery, New Haven, Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"HD0419","mother_id":"I00146"},"prominent_name_reason":"John Pierpont (1740-1805) — great-grandfather of J.P. Morgan (1837-1913). Chain: John Pierpont (H00388) → James Pierpont → John Pierpont the poet (1785-1866, abolitionist) → Juliet Pierpont × Junius Spencer Morgan → John Pierpont Morgan. J.P. Morgan's middle name \"Pierpont\" commemorates this descent from the Pierpont family of New Haven — founded by Rev. James Pierpont, who married Mary Hooker (H00034). Thomas Hooker's great-great-great-granddaughter's grandson became the most powerful financier in American history.","tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 388"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00494","children_ids":["H00976","HD1550","H00977","H00978","H00979","H00980","H00981","H00982","H00983","H00984","X00998"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1767,"date_month":12,"date_day":26},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"H00451","date_year":1789,"date_month":2,"date_day":26,"children_ids":["HD0558","HD0559","HD0560","HD0561","HD0562","HD0563"]}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"John Pierpont","notes":"Sources also give surname as \"Pierrepont\" — alternate spelling","first_name":"John","last_name":"Pierpont","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Great-grandfather of J.P. Morgan","body":"His great-grandson was John Pierpont Morgan (1837-1913), the financier whose name 'J.P. Morgan' carries forward this Pierpont line. Through his son James Pierpont and grandson John Pierpont the poet, the name traveled four generations to one of America's most consequential bankers."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Lived in old Pierpont mansion, New Haven","body":"Timothy Dwight described him as 'a large landholder who lived in the old family-mansion at New Haven.' He had ten children, of whom only four reached adulthood and only three married."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Family later restored 'Pierrepont' French spelling","body":"He was born 'Pierpont' but late in his life, around 1802, Hezekiah Beers Pierpont requested the family restore the original French 'Pierrepont' spelling. Hezekiah did not adopt it himself for business reasons; descendants split between the two spellings thereafter."}],"slug":"john-pierpont-1740"},"X00494":{"id":"X00494","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1744},"death":{"year":1835},"gender":"female","parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00388","date_year":1767,"date_month":12,"date_day":26,"children_ids":["H00976","HD1550","H00977","H00978","H00979","H00980","H00981","H00982","H00983","H00984","X00998"]}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Beers","first_name":"Sarah","maiden_name":"Beers","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"She buried seven children and lived to ninety","body":"Sarah Beers married John Pierpont and bore ten children, but only four reached adulthood; she named three daughters Sarah and lost two as infants and the third at fourteen. She lived to ninety, outliving her husband by thirty years."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"The British seized her home as a hospital","body":"During the 1779 British invasion of New Haven, soldiers raided the house her husband John Pierpont had built and took it for use as a hospital and headquarters. The home stood at the center of the town's worst wartime days."},{"number":3,"category":"military","header":"Her brother guarded the captured spy Major André","body":"Sarah's brother, Captain Nathan Beers, commanded the guard over the British spy Major John André at his trial and execution in 1780. André's hanging, in the wake of Benedict Arnold's treason, was among the most talked-of events of the war."}],"slug":"sarah-beers-1744"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{"INST014":{"id":"INST014","primary_name":"American Geographical Society","name":"American Geographical Society","alt_names":[],"type":"learned_society","founding_year":1851,"location":{"city":"New York","state":"New York"},"primary_persons":[],"hooker_connected_people":["HD2152","HD1533","HD0867"],"person_ids":[],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Online vital records","note":"Wikipedia American Geographical Society"}],"notes":"Founded 1851 by 31 New Yorkers, originally to organize a search for the lost Franklin Polar Expedition. Among the founders: Henry Evelyn Pierrepont (HD1533, gen 6) and Rev. Joshua Leavitt (HD0867, gen 6) — two Hooker descendants through entirely separate branches, almost certainly unaware of their shared ancestry. Pierrepont served on its Council 1852-1862. Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Geographical_Society"}},"crossConnections":[{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"HD0867","link_text":"Rev. Joshua Leavitt","display_label":"Henry Evelyn Pierrepont co-founded the American Geographical Society (1851) alongside.","slug":"joshua-leavitt-1794"}]}